elements of modernisation matter for their area. Which sectors saw the greatest degree of change? Do terms such as 'modern welfare state' or 'social investment state' have any resonance? They also examine change over time with reference to the terms of the government. Was reform a fairly continuous event, or was it concentrated in certain periods? Finally, the contributors give an assessment of likely policy direction under a future Labour or Conservative government. Previous books in the trilogy are New Labour, new welfare state? (1999) and Evaluating New Labour's welfare reforms (2002) (see below). The works should be read by academics, undergraduates and post-graduates on courses in social policy, public policy and political science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPublic welfarezGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aBaldwin, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharman, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenney, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrowolsky, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrakeford, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreener, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLister, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLund, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKay, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuschamp, Yolande, econtributor.4ctb4